The score differences between the A and B text options per question is fairly normally distributed. For the absolute values of those differences, it is skewed. Across the domains, Physics is the most skewed in its absolute score differences and Social is less so. Across platform types, news and blogs have outliers but the ranges of the five platforms is relatively similar though their distributions differ.

Overall¶

  • There is no clear/strong relationship between the (absolute) score difference of text A and B and the performance of the computational score (performance compared to human assessment).
  • However, for scores with high human expert agreement (at least 4 of 5 respondents have same answer), the computational score matches more with the human assessment than when just looking at the entire pool (aka also the scores with low human agreement). In other words, our simple computational score performs well (about 80% match) for assessments when the human agreement is also high.
  • TLDR; Our survey provides validation for our computational measure. From our survey, we look at the survey items with high human agreement. Of those survey items with high human agreement, roughly 80% of the responses match the respective computational measure's assessment. However, the survey results also highlight how information loss is a difficult task for humans, generally rife with uncertainty.
